Reversion (Terminal)
git revert &lt;commit hash&gt;



If you want to revert changes with the terminal you can use git revert together with the commit hash you want to revert to.

Pushing a new branch

git push --set-upstream origin &lt;new-branch-name&gt;



Pushing a new branch using JupyterLab is exactly the same as you are used to with the ‚Äúpush‚Äù button. However, there is a slight change in the command when you are pushing a branch you created locally with the terminal. Instead of git push you will have to write:
git push --set-upstream origin &lt;new-branch-name&gt;
This command decides what the new branch will be called on the remote GitHub repo. It is recommended that you use the same name as you use locally, and using a different name is rarely necessary. You don‚Äôt need to worry about remembering this command, because git will remind you in the case you forget to specify it as you can see in the image.
After pushing the new branch report to the remote you will notice that the local branch report and the remote branch origin/report are placed in the same commit when you read the history of the project. This means that your remote repository is synchronized with your local repository.

Merging branches (Terminal)

git merge &lt;branch&gt;



If you want to use the terminal to merge the branches and you are currently working on the main branch, you can type git merge &lt;branch&gt; to merge the commits from the branch with the new feature into the main branch. In this slide, we merged in the changes of the branched named report into main by typing git merge report while having the main branch active.

Pro tip 1: Change image size
You can use the following HTML tag to change the displayed size of an image:
&lt;img src="&lt;PATH_TO_FILE&gt;" width="400px"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;



You can use the HTML tag that you see in the slide to change the displayed size of an image:
&lt;img src="&lt;PATH_TO_FILE&gt;" width="400px"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;
Note that in width=400px, px is optional. Instead of px (which stands for ‚Äúpixel‚Äù), you can also use % to specify the width relative to the original width of the image. For example, the image HTML tag with width="150%"
&lt;img src="&lt;PATH_TO_FILE&gt;" width="150%"&gt;&lt;/img&gt;
enlarges the displayed image by a factor of 1.5.
